
Balance is a complex motor skill that integrates and coordinates several different body systems @horakClinicalAssessmentBalance1997. Assessments of balance can be useful for diagnosis (e.g., early detection of fall risk in individuals @manciniRelevanceClinicalBalance2010) or in rehabilitation (e.g, tailoring treatment strategies to the individual @visserClinicalUtilityPosturography2008). 

Clinical assessments of balance tend to be limited to practical, easily useable methods (see Chapter 1.3 for a brief overview of tests and quantitative methods). However, pure qualitative methods may not be enough to fully grasp the complex motor skills that underlie balance @paillardTechniquesMethodsTesting2015 @visserClinicalUtilityPosturography2008. Visual analysis may also be subjective and suffer from tester bias @manciniRelevanceClinicalBalance2010.    Quantitative analysis could provide valuable into patient balance. Detailed kinematic data could note subtle trends that visual assessment may miss, and would provide quantitative metrics of individual trends in 
balance over time, whether it be in aging or recovery. 

One such assessment is the Modified Clinical Test of Sensory Interaction on Balance (CTSIB-M)@ModifiedClinicalTest2013. In this test, participants maintain balance under four conditions that systematically vary visual input and surface stability (eyes open/closed; firm/foam surface). These manipulations provide a graded increase in task difficulty, allowing for controlled assessment of postural stability across conditions.

Here, we use a six-camera video-based motion capture system to measure postural metrics in participants completing the CTSIB-M. Many markerless systems are often validated on dynamic movements. However, evaluating a static balance task where movement of the body is minimal also provides key characterization of the system. As such, we evaluate whether the system can detect the expected increases in postural sway across progressively challenging conditions, and how accurate the magnitude of those changes is relative to a marker-based reference system.



